    <chapter-placement version="2.0.0">
      <reasoning-chapter-placement>
        First chapter of Act 3. Just when they've learned to trust themselves, trust gets COMPLICATED. Florence's deception revealed: she's been "interpreting" Elder Twist's cryptic fragments into helpful advice, but actually fabricating most of it. Her advice WAS good—HER wisdom—but using Elder Twist as cover.

        Plants feel DEEPLY betrayed. They trusted Elder Twist, not Florence's judgment. But Kira sees it differently: "The advice helped. Florence was trying to help us survive. Intent matters." She defends Florence even as others condemn—because Kira doesn't have the same reverence for authority, AND because she's starting to realize she CARES about these plants. She's not neutral anymore.

        This is where Kira's "everything is temporary" starts breaking down. If she didn't care, she'd stay out of it. But she CAN'T stay out of it. Florence is her FRIEND. Scout learned flower-language because Florence taught them. The plants taught her to communicate. She's not an observer anymore—she's invested.

        Florence's arc: alienation, guilt, but also the seed of redemption. She gave good advice but didn't trust her own voice to be heard.
      </reasoning-chapter-placement>
      <chapter-objective>
        Reveal Florence's deception. Plants feel betrayed. But Kira DEFENDS Florence—the advice was good, intent matters. This is Kira choosing to be invested, no longer neutral, caring about her found family even when it's complicated. Begin Florence's isolation and eventual path to redemption.
      </chapter-objective>
